        "discriminators": [
          "A structure coming down: a long, LF-heavy rumble carrying a dense, irregular train of debris impacts. The defining MEASUREMENT is that the energy is SPREAD rather than front-loaded — envelope_temporal_centroid sits near the middle of the file and transient_count is high.",
          "Against EXPLOSIONS-REAL, the key boundary: an explosion is ONE front-loaded burst (low temporal centroid, few onsets); a collapse is MANY events unfolding over seconds. That comparison is genuinely measurable and is what lifts this above semantic_only.",
          "Against DESTRUCTION-CRASH & DEBRIS: a collapse is slower, heavier and more LF-dominated (masonry and timber giving way, a groan before the fall); a crash begins with a single hard impact and then sheds debris, so it is more front-loaded and brighter. A weak lean only."
        ],
